column9: C1. There is not enough information to definitively say that climate change is real.
column10: C2. The response to  climate change is not going to be positive.  The same mistakes will keep happening.
column11: C3. Climate variation is normal, so why should this be a problem?
column12: C4. More educational programmes are needed to increase public awareness about climate change.
column13: C5. Climate change will not be a problem because there will be technological solutions available.
column14: C6. I don't trust what scientists say about climate change.
column15: C7. I don't trust what I hear about climate change from government.
column16: C8. We need strong political leadership to do something about climate change.
column17: C9. I think it is safe to say climate change is here.
column18: C10. I'm not going to do anything to address climate change because it is not a major issue.
column19: C11. There's not much point in me doing anything to fix this. No-one else is going to.
column20: C12. It's difficult to trust what comes out in the media on the issue of climate change.
column21: C13. It is already too late to do anything, as any action to stop climate change will take a long time to take effect.
column22: C14. I'm not concerned enough to do anything drastic about this, such as participate in political action.
column23: C15. It is unfair that we are going to leave the climate in a mess for future generations.
column24: C16. We should pay for greenhouse emissions.
column25: C17. We can adapt to the coming changes.
column26: C18. It is clear that we are already entering the zone of dangerous climate change.
column27: C19. I care about the planet.
column28: C20. I don't know what to do. I'm very concerned and would like to do something, but I don't have a realistic shortlist of things that would really make a difference.
column29: C21. Australia does not owe it to the rest of the world to reduce emissions and suffer economically.
column30: C22. If Australia reduces greenhouse gases it won't make a difference. That will just shift Australian jobs to other countries.
column31: C23. This is so depressing and is so out of our control.
column32: C24. I believe that the difference we can have as an individual, in Australia, is so minimal that our actions are worthless.
column33: C25. Australia is particularly vulnerable to climate change, and it is in our interest to help find an effective global solution.
column34: C26. We need laws addressing climate change because people are not going to volunteer to change.
column35: C27. I want to do something, but it is too big and too hard.
column36: C28. When I read in the paper that climate change is not true, I start to have doubts about whether it is changing.
column37: C29. Doing something to reduce emissions feels a bit hopeless but I just want to feel that I'm doing the most I can.
column38: C30. The fate of the planet is too important to be left to market forces.
column39: C31. Australia's emissions are tiny, so it's not up to us to act.
column40: C32. Governments should take a far greater role in preparing towns and cities to adapt to the impacts of climate change.
column41: C33. Failure to address climate change is the fault of political leaders.
